<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-06-11T00:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-06-11T00:00:00-05:00" n="464" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d464">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/13189: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Hong Kong</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Southard</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Hong
                                        Kong</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-06-11T13:00:00+08:00">June 11, 1938—1
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received June 11—6 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>In continuation of my telegram of this date,<note n="52" xml:id="d464fn52">Not printed.</note> Japanese Consul General
                            expressed the informal and strictly confidential opinion that <pb facs="0354" n="350" xml:id="pg_350"/> bombing would continue in
                            Canton and other places in South China thus making highly advisable
                            identification of all American property.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Southard</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>